  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">Anne W. Weston was very sick, but refused to call a doctor. Dr. Amos Farnsworth drove Lucia Weston from town to Groton expecting Anne to follow in a few days; she must therefore try to get well. Anne gives an account of the family at Summer Street, and of the departure of Warren Weston. James S. Gibbons arrived as a visitor on Sunday morning. Edmund Quincy came after breakfast, and they talked all morning. Further callers and guests afforded &quot;quite a brilliant time.&quot; Members of the family went to see &quot;the floral procession of Mr. Barnard&apos;s children.&quot; The Catholic Temperance procession was beautiful. Tonight, Anne will remain at home, as she does not care for &quot;standing gaping on the Common...Nothing but being with a brother ever made it tolerable to me, so wafting a few sighs to Demerara, I rejoice that I have no temptation to go.&quot; [The reference to Demerara is presumably to Richard Hildreth, who resided in Georgetown, Demerara, British Guiana (now known as Guyana).]</subfield>
